---
import ProjectDetail from '../../layouts/ProjectDetail.astro';

const demoVideo = '/videos/expression-detection-demo.mov';
---

<ProjectDetail
  title="Expression Detection"
  description="Real-time facial expression detection using dlib facial landmarks and geometric heuristics — no ML model required."
  tags={['Computer Vision', 'dlib', 'OpenCV']}
  github="https://github.com/MariamKhubashvilii/expression-detection"
  accent="pink"
  demoVideo={demoVideo}
>
  <section class="project-grid">
    <article class="project-card summary-card">
      <h2>Project summary</h2>
      <p>
        A real-time facial expression detector built with OpenCV and dlib. It uses 68 facial landmarks and simple geometric heuristics — not machine learning — to classify expressions and react with spoken comments via macOS <code>say</code>.
      </p>
      <div class="summary-list">
        <div>
          <strong>Interpretable rules</strong>
          <p>All classification is threshold-based on mouth, eye, and brow geometry — fully transparent and tunable.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <strong>Temporal smoothing</strong>
          <p>Majority vote across frames reduces flicker; audio feedback has a cooldown to prevent spam.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="project-card detail-card">
      <h2>What this project shows</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>dlib frontal face detection and 68-point landmarks.</li>
        <li>Geometric feature extraction (mouth, EAR, brow gap).</li>
        <li>Rule-based classification into five expressions.</li>
        <li>Frame-level smoothing and audio reactions.</li>
      </ul>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="project-section">
    <div class="section-content">
      <h2>How it works</h2>
      <p>
        The webcam captures live video, dlib detects faces and extracts 68 landmarks per face. Features are normalized using outer eye-corner distance, then mouth curvature, eye aspect ratio, and brow gap feed into threshold rules that classify happy, sad, angry, surprised, or neutral.
      </p>

      <div class="section-grid">
        <div>
          <h3>Expressions</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Happy</li>
            <li>Sad</li>
            <li>Angry</li>
            <li>Surprised</li>
            <li>Neutral</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3>Why heuristics?</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Interpretable facial geometry</li>
            <li>Ratios that scale across face sizes</li>
            <li>Clear thresholds you can tune</li>
            <li>Fast, lightweight, easy to debug</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="project-section project-usage">
    <h2>Run it</h2>
    <p>
      Install dependencies (<code>dlib</code>, <code>opencv-python</code>), ensure you have a webcam, and run the main script. macOS is required for the built-in <code>say</code> audio feedback command.
    </p>
    <div class="usage-card">
      <div>
        <strong>Requirements</strong>
        <p>Python 3.8+, macOS, webcam, dlib, OpenCV</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <strong>Best for</strong>
        <p>Exploring how far rule-based CV can go before reaching for a trained model.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</ProjectDetail>
